Ellen DeGeneres is giving $1.6 million in college scholarships to an entire class of 41 kids from Summit Academy Charter School in Brooklyn, New York. It's the single biggest gift The Ellen Show has ever given, and it allows the kids to apply to any state university in New York and attend the next four years free of cost. According to the school founder Natasha Campbell, only 4% adults in their Red Hook neighborhood have attended college and more than 28% of children under 16 live in poverty.

Halima Aden is breaking barriers in the fashion industry. The 19-year-old from Minnesota has become the first hijab-wearing model to sign a contract with IMG Models Worldwide, the premier modeling agency that also reps supermodels Gigi Hadid and Kate Moss. Aden made history at the New York Fashion Week when she walked in the Kanye West show last week, and today she featured in the Alberta Ferretti show during Milan Fashion Week. Aden was born in a Kenyan refugee camp, and traces her heritage to Somalia, one of the countries from which Donald Trump wanted to ban immigrants. The 19-year-old first came into the spotlight in 2016 when she competed in the Miss Minnesota USA event wearing a hijab in all the rounds, and a burkini during the swimsuit segment‚Äîa first for the pageant.

(üì∑: Getty Images at the ALBERTA FERRETTI - official page show during Milan Fashion Week.)
